# fedviz

**Framework-agnostic monitoring for federated and distributed ML.**  
Drop-in like W&B, but built for federated training.

---

## Install

```bash
pip install fedviz           # core only (zero dependencies)
pip install fedviz[wandb]    # + W&B integration
pip install fedviz[flower]   # + Flower adapter
pip install fedviz[ray]      # + Ray adapter
pip install fedviz[all]      # everything
```

---

## Quickstart — any framework

```python
import fedviz
from fedviz import ClientMetrics

fedviz.init(wandb_project="my-fl-project", algorithm="FedAvg")

for rnd in range(num_rounds):
    fedviz.log_round_start(rnd)

    # ... your training code, any framework ...

    fedviz.log_round(
        round=rnd,
        clients=[
            ClientMetrics(
                client_id="node-01",
                local_accuracy=0.85,
                local_loss=0.32,
                num_samples=500,
                gradient_norm=1.24,
                bytes_sent=4_200_000,
                train_time_sec=12.1,
                cpu_pct=72.0,
                lat=37.7, lng=-122.4, city="San Francisco", country="US",
            )
        ],
        global_accuracy=0.84,
        global_loss=0.29,
    )

fedviz.finish()
```

---

## Flower — one wrapper, zero client changes

```python
from flwr.server.strategy import FedProx
from fedviz.adapters.flower import FedVizStrategy
import fedviz

fedviz.init(wandb_project="my-project", algorithm="FedProx")

strategy = FedVizStrategy(inner=FedProx(...))  # that's it

fl.server.start_server(strategy=strategy, ...)
fedviz.finish()
```

Clients just include metrics in their `fit()` return dict — no fedviz import required:

```python
def fit(self, parameters, config):
    # ... train ...
    return parameters, len(dataset), {
        "gradient_norm":  1.24,
        "train_time_sec": 12.1,
        "cpu_pct":        72.0,
        "bytes_sent":     4_200_000,
    }
```

---

## Ray — decorator or manual

```python
from fedviz.adapters.ray_adapter import fedviz_ray_round

@fedviz_ray_round(round_arg="server_round")
def aggregate(server_round, futures):
    results = ray.get(futures)
    # ... aggregation ...
    return global_acc, global_loss, results  # fedviz auto-logs

for rnd in range(num_rounds):
    futures = [client.train.remote(rnd) for client in selected]
    aggregate(server_round=rnd, futures=futures)
```

---

## Adopt an existing W&B run

```python
import wandb, fedviz

wandb.init(project="my-project")   # your existing code
fedviz.init()                      # auto-adopts the active run
```

---

## What gets logged to W&B

| Metric namespace | What it tracks |
|---|---|
| `round/accuracy`, `round/loss` | Global model performance per round |
| `round/participation_rate` | % of selected clients that completed |
| `round/num_stragglers` | Straggler count per round |
| `round/duration_sec` | Wall time per round |
| `comm/total_bytes_mb` | Total communication volume |
| `comm/bytes_per_client_mb` | Communication efficiency |
| `agg/gradient_norm` | Aggregated gradient norm |
| `agg/gradient_divergence` | Std dev of per-client norms — **non-IID signal** |
| `agg/aggregation_time_sec` | Server aggregation compute time |
| `client/<id>/accuracy` | Per-client accuracy |
| `client/<id>/gradient_norm` | Per-client gradient norm |
| `client/<id>/staleness` | Async FL staleness (rounds behind) |
| `client/<id>/bytes_sent_mb` | Per-client upload volume |
| `client/<id>/train_time_sec` | Per-client training time |
| `sys/<id>/cpu_pct` | Per-client CPU utilisation |
| `sys/<id>/gpu_util_pct` | Per-client GPU utilisation |
| `event/client_dropout` | Dropout counter per round |
| `event/comm_failure` | Communication failure counter |

All metrics use `round` as the x-axis via `wandb.define_metric()`.  
Checkpoints are logged as versioned W&B Artifacts.  
Client dropouts and comm failures fire W&B Alerts.

---

## Custom emitter

fedviz is fully pluggable. Implement `.emit(event: FLEvent)` and pass it in:

```python
class MyMLflowEmitter:
    def emit(self, event):
        if event.event_type == EventType.ROUND_END:
            mlflow.log_metrics({
                "accuracy": event.round_metrics.global_accuracy,
                "loss":     event.round_metrics.global_loss,
            }, step=event.round)

    def finish(self):
        mlflow.end_run()

fedviz.init(emitters=[MyMLflowEmitter()])
```

---

## Architecture

```
Your training code  ──► fedviz.log_round(...)
                              │
                    ┌─────────▼──────────┐
                    │   FLEvent schema    │  ← universal envelope
                    └─────────┬──────────┘
                              │
              ┌───────────────┼───────────────┐
              ▼               ▼               ▼
       WandbEmitter    FedVizServer     CustomEmitter
       (wandb.log)    (SQLite + SSE)   (MLflow, etc.)
```

The schema owns the data. Emitters own the transformation. Neither knows about the other.
